com.esri.mo2.data.omc
Class TileCache

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--com.esri.mo2.data.omc.TileCache
public class TileCache
extends Object

A Tile Cache is a Collection of visited Tiles (Areas), where each tile has a collection of visited RemoteFeatureClass. Each RemoteFeatureClass has a spatial collection of Cached Features. Each cached feature inturn has a collection of attribute values and a collection of geometries as different scales.

The tile cache has a fixed-size collection of Tiles. The tiles are deprecated on a LRU basis. Due to the large amount of data that the tile cache can hold, a disk cache is associated with it to move onto the disk the least recently used data.

Several static properties of the TileCache may be customized - the max number of objects stored in memory, the max size disk file, the disk file name, and whether or not the cache clips spatial query geometries. However, if any such changes are made,they must be made before the first call to TileCache.get() - after that call, any changes will be ignored once the TileCache instance has been created. Of coruse, if TileCache.close() is called, then a subsequent call to TileCache.get() will use whatever are the current values for these static properties.

close

public static final void close()
Closes the TileCache, removes the associated object database file and consequently clears away all features that are currently stored in the cache. It is possible to continue using TileCache, by subsequent use of TileCache.get(). Note that the first time the TileCache is used after close() has been called, a completely new object database file will be created - possibly with the same file name as before.

isVisited

public int isVisited(RemoteFeatureClass remoteFeatureClass,
                     double scale,
                     Polygon area)
Determines if any/some/all of the given area has been retrieved to cache at the specified map scale.

Parameters:
remoteFeatureClass - the feature class
scale - the map scale
area - the polygon
Returns:
the value NONE, PARTIAL, or COMPLETE depending on if the area has not (yet) been retrieved, has been partially retrieved, or has been completely retrieved at this moment - this status can change!

Note: The specified area will be intersected with the RemoteFeatureClass' extent before testing is performed. This is because cache Tiles do not record anything outside the extent of a RemoteFeatureClass.

See Also:
NONE, PARTIAL, COMPLETE

fetch

public void fetch(RemoteFeatureClass remoteFeatureClass,
                  double scale,
                  Polygon area,
                  Object user)
Invokes the retrieval process to start for all or some of the given area. Ensure that you first call the isVisited method to determine if a retrieval is needed. If isVisited returns PARTIAL, only that part of the specified area that is not already within cache will be retrieved.

If this method call is "non-blocking", the retrieval will be started in a separate Thread, and the fetch method will return straight away. You can supply any "user" object which may be helpful for tracking the retrieval thread.

Parameters:
remoteFeatureClass - the RemoteFeatureClass to be retrieved
scale - the current map scale that is used to select the scale dependent features from server
area - the bounding area to be retrieved - this may be altered when Tile construction occurs
user - an optional object that will be passed back in a RemoteQuery - this won't be altered and can be used to track this retrieval, null is ok
See Also:
isVisited(com.esri.mo2.data.omc.RemoteFeatureClass, double, com.esri.mo2.cs.geom.Polygon)

setClipToExtent

public static final void setClipToExtent(boolean clipToExtent)
Allows developers to choose whether or not the TileCache will modify the geometry within each RemoteQuery sent to a RemoteFeatureClass.retrieve() such that the geometry is clipped by the RemoteFeatureClass' Extent property. When the TileCache performs this clipping, then retrievals are more efficient, because it is expected that data in the remote server does not exist outside the Extent - this is most appropriate when the remote server does not allow modifications to the underlying data. However, if the remote server allows the underlying data to be modified on-the-fly, then it may be better to stop the TileCache from performing this clipping, since it might lead to loss of data on the client-side. In particular, Features that have been newly added to the server, that lie outside the defined Extent would never be retrieved if the TileCache performs clipping.

Note: this method must be called before a call to TileCache.get() constructs a new TileCache instance - normally this is the first time that TileCache.get() is called, or the first time after TileCache.close() has been called.

Parameters:
clipToExtent - true == the TileCache will clip all spatial requests, false == no clipping

getClipToExtent

public final boolean getClipToExtent()
Returns the state of extent clipping for the current TileCache. If setClipToExtent() has not been called, then the default value for this property is "false".

the extent clipping status
